AB  - The twisted-tape-induced swirl flow heat transfer due to exponentially increasing heat inputs with various exponential periods and twisted-tape-induced pressure drop were systematically measured with mass velocity G = 4120 to 13 570 kg/m(2)/s, inlet liquid temperature T-in = 300.13 to 305.78 K and inlet pressure P-in = 866.52 to 945.86 kPa by an experimental water loop flow. Measurements were made on a 59.2 mm effective length and its three sections (upper, mid and lower positions), which were spot-welded four potential taps on the outer surface of a 6 mm inner diameter, a 69.6 mm heated length and a 0.4 mm thickness of Platinum circular test tube with the twisted-tape insert. The SUS304 twisted-tape of width w = 5.6 mm, thickness delta(T) = 0.6 mm, total length l = 372 mm, pitch of 180 degrees rotation H = 20.34 mm and twist ratio y = H/d = 3.39 was employed in this work. On the other hand, theoretical equations for k-epsilon turbulence model in a circular tube of a 6 mm in diameter and a 636 mm long with the twisted-tape insert were numerically solved for heating of water with heated section of a 6 mm in diameter and a 70 mm long by using PHOENICS code under the same conditions as the experimental ones considering the temperature dependence of thermo-physical properties concerned. The twisted-tape of w = 5.6 mm, delta(T) = 0.6 mm, l = 370 mm, H = 20 mm and y = 3.33 was installed under the same experimental position. The surface heat flux q and the average surface temperature T-s,T-av on the circular tube with the twisted-tape of y = 3.33 obtained theoretically were compared with the corresponding experimental values on q versus the temperature difference between average heater inner surface temperature and liquid bulk mean temperature Delta T-L [=T-s,T-av - T-L, T-L = (T-in + T-out)/2] graph. The numerical solutions of q and Delta T-L are almost in good agreement with the corresponding experimental values of q and Delta T-L with the deviations less than 0% to +20% for the range of Delta T-L tested here. The numerical solutions of the local surface temperature (T-s)(z), local average liquid temperature (T-f,T-av)(z) and local liquid pressure drop Delta P-z were also compared with the corresponding experimental data of (T)2, (T-f,T-av)(z) and Delta P-z versus heated length L or distance from inlet of the test section Z graph, respectively. The numerical solutions of (T-s)(z), (T-f,T-av)(z) and Delta P-z are within +/- 5% difference of the corresponding experimental data on (T-s)(z), (T-f,T-av)(z) and Delta P-z. The thickness of the conductive sub-layer delta(CSL) [=(Delta r)(out)/2] and the non-dimensional thickness of the conductive sub-layer y(CSL)(+) [=(f(F)/2)(0.5) rho(l)u delta(CSL)/mu(l)] for the turbulent heat transfer on the circular tube with the twisted-tape insert are clarified based on the numerical solutions at the swirl velocity u(sw) ranging from 5.39 to 18.03 m/s. The correlations of delta(CSL) and y(CSL)(+) for twisted-tape-induced swirl flow heat transfer in a vertical circular tube are derived. (c) 2013 Elsevier B.V. All rights reserved.
