AB  - In the ultrasonic in-line inspection of longdistance oil and gas pipelines, accurate analysis of the structural size of pipeline defects based on echo data is an important part of nondestructive testing and the basis for subsequent risk assessment of pipelines containing defects. The key to echo analysis is to extract the characteristic parameters corresponding to the defect from the detection signal. By carrying out the ultrasonic in-line inspection experiment of the pipeline with volumetric defects on the outer wall, the amplitude ratio of the characteristic points is used as a feature to recognize the boundary of the volumetric defects. Based on experimental data obtained from piezoelectric ultrasonic testing, a methodology for identifying the boundaries of volumetric defects has been developed. The results show that the proposed method can effectively identify the boundary of volumetric defects with a high recognition accuracy of 3 & times; 5 mm, the maximum deviation distance under standard conditions is 1.7 mm, which has a certain guiding significance for the identification of pipeline defect boundaries in practical engineering.
